Credit du Nord said it had profit of 62.7 million French francs ($9.5 million) in the first half of 1989, reversing a year-earlier loss of 2.6 million francs. 

The Paris-based retail banking unit of financial services concern Cie.
Financiere de Paribas said the first-half report marked a further step in the turnaround that began when it posted profit of 59.3 million francs for all of 1988 after a year-earlier loss of 157.6 million francs. 

Credit du Nord said the rebound was largely due to a restructuring that helped it cut general operating expenses by 3.5% in the first half.
It also said previous moves to reinforce loan reserves helped to limit new provisions for risky loans to 391 million francs, compared with 581 million francs in the first half of 1988.
